We also now actually use glow_size instead of the hardcoded body.radius * 5.5, so bigger/brighter stars will have larger glows.

FIX 3 — Wrong Constant is Capping the Substep Count
Severity: 🔴 Performance Bug at High Speeds
What's Wrong
Your simulation splits each frame's time into small "substeps" to keep the physics stable. You have two constants with very similar names:

Constant	Value	Meaning
MAX_SUBSTEP_S	86400.0	Max size of one substep in seconds (1 day)
MAX_SUBSTEPS	512	Max number of substeps per frame
The cap line is supposed to use MAX_SUBSTEPS (the count), but it uses MAX_SUBSTEP_S (the seconds value) by mistake.

In practice, at normal speeds the number of substeps is small anyway so you never hit the cap and nothing breaks. But crank the speed multiplier up and Python tries to cap the substep count at 86400 instead of 512 — so instead of doing at most 512 small steps, it might try to do 86,400 of them. Your frame will take several seconds to compute and the app freezes.

Find It
Search your file for:

substeps = min(MAX_SUBSTEP_S
You will see:

        substeps = min(MAX_SUBSTEP_S, max(1, math.ceil(dt / safe_dt)))
Delete This
        substeps = min(MAX_SUBSTEP_S, max(1, math.ceil(dt / safe_dt)))
Replace With This
        # MAX_SUBSTEPS is the integer count cap (512)
        # MAX_SUBSTEP_S is the seconds-per-substep cap (86400.0) — different thing!
        substeps = min(MAX_SUBSTEPS, max(1, math.ceil(dt / safe_dt)))
Why It Works
It's a one-word change. MAX_SUBSTEP_S → MAX_SUBSTEPS. The correct constant is the integer 512, which properly caps the loop at 512 iterations per frame no matter how fast the simulation is running.

This is a classic "typo that only hurts you in edge cases" bug — perfectly fine at default speed, catastrophic at 1024× speed.

