Gravity Sim — Visual Rendering Bugs: Root Cause & Fixes
The Short Answer
Every single visual bug you described — stars not moving, trails running away, planets stuck near the sun — all come from one bug: the matrix multiplication order in _model_matrix. Everything else is a side effect of that one line.

Why Your Symptoms All Connect
Here's what's happening under the hood:

Your simulation has two separate "worlds":

Physics world — positions stored in real metres (e.g. Earth = 149 billion metres from Sun)
GL world — positions scaled down to fit the screen (divided by SCALE = 2 AU)
Every frame, three things use the body's position:



Thing	How it gets position	Uses matrix?
Trail points	body.pos / SCALE directly	❌ No
Light positions	body.pos / SCALE directly	❌ No
Sphere (the visible ball)	body.pos / SCALE → then through _model_matrix	✅ Yes
Trails and lights get the correct position directly. The visible sphere goes through _model_matrix — which is broken — so it ends up in the wrong place.

That's why trails and lights go to where the star SHOULD be, but the star itself stays nearly still. The sphere isn't where the physics says it is.

The Actual Bug — Matrix Multiplication Order
Open your file and find _model_matrix. You'll see this on the last line:

return S @ Zt @ R @ T
In 3D graphics, you build a "model matrix" by combining four transforms:

S = Scale (resize the sphere to the correct visual size)
Zt = Tilt (axial tilt, like Earth's 23.5°)
R = Rotate (spin on its axis)
T = Translate (move to world position)
These must happen in a specific order. Think of it like getting a parcel ready to ship:

Put the item in the box (scale)
Seal the box (tilt/rotate)
Address the label and send it (translate)
If you address the box first and THEN resize it, the address gets shrunk with the box. That's exactly what's happening: S @ Zt @ R @ T means scale is applied last, which shrinks the translation too.

The Numbers
Earth's radius (GL display size) is approximately 0.00364. Earth's GL position from the Sun is 1.0 AU / (2 AU SCALE) = 0.5 units.

With the wrong order, the translation gets multiplied by the radius:

0.5 × 0.00364 = 0.00182 units from the Sun
That's basically sitting ON the Sun. Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn all do the same thing — they all collapse to a tiny cluster right at the Sun.

Binary stars have a bigger radius (~0.07), so they collapse less but still appear much closer together than they should, making them look like they're spinning in place.

Fix 1 — The Matrix Order (Fixes ALL Your Visual Bugs)
Find It
Search for:

return S @ Zt @ R @ T
Delete This
    def _model_matrix(self, gl_pos, radius, rotation, axial_tilt_deg):
        tilt_rad = math.radians(axial_tilt_deg)
        T  = matrix44.create_from_translation(gl_pos.astype('f4'), dtype='f4')
        Zt = matrix44.create_from_z_rotation(tilt_rad,             dtype='f4')
        R  = matrix44.create_from_y_rotation(rotation,             dtype='f4')
        S  = matrix44.create_from_scale([radius]*3,                dtype='f4')
        return S @ Zt @ R @ T
Replace With This
    def _model_matrix(self, gl_pos, radius, rotation, axial_tilt_deg):
        tilt_rad = math.radians(axial_tilt_deg)
        T  = matrix44.create_from_translation(gl_pos.astype('f4'), dtype='f4')
        Zt = matrix44.create_from_z_rotation(tilt_rad,             dtype='f4')
        R  = matrix44.create_from_y_rotation(rotation,             dtype='f4')
        S  = matrix44.create_from_scale([radius]*3,                dtype='f4')
        # Correct order (read right to left):
        # 1. S  — resize the unit sphere to body.radius
        # 2. Zt — apply axial tilt (e.g. Earth's 23.5 degree lean)
        # 3. R  — spin on the now-tilted axis
        # 4. T  — move the finished sphere to its world position
        return T @ R @ Zt @ S
What You'll See After This Fix
✅ Binary stars orbit each other across real visible distance
✅ Planets spread out from the Sun at correct distances
✅ Trails follow the actual star spheres instead of running away from them
✅ Lighting comes from where the stars visually are
